Trigger covers both UPDATE and DELETE; materialized view for audit; serializable isolation for the concurrent write skew case.

```
CREATE OR REPLACE FUNCTION check_team_admin_coverage()
RETURNS TRIGGER LANGUAGE plpgsql AS $$
DECLARE
  remaining_admins INT;
  chk_team_id INT;
  chk_user_id INT;
BEGIN
  IF TG_OP = 'DELETE' THEN
    chk_team_id := OLD.team_id;
    chk_user_id := OLD.user_id;
    IF OLD.role <> 'admin' THEN RETURN OLD; END IF;
  ELSE
    chk_team_id := NEW.team_id;
    chk_user_id := NEW.user_id;
    IF NOT (NEW.role <> 'admin' AND OLD.role = 'admin') THEN RETURN NEW; END IF;
  END IF;

  SELECT COUNT(*) INTO remaining_admins
  FROM team_members
  WHERE team_id = chk_team_id
    AND role = 'admin'
    AND user_id <> chk_user_id;

  IF remaining_admins = 0 THEN
    RAISE EXCEPTION
      'Cannot remove last admin from team %', chk_team_id;
  END IF;

  IF TG_OP = 'DELETE' THEN RETURN OLD; ELSE RETURN NEW; END IF;
END;
$$;

CREATE TRIGGER team_admin_coverage_check
BEFORE UPDATE OR DELETE ON team_members
FOR EACH ROW EXECUTE FUNCTION check_team_admin_coverage();

CREATE MATERIALIZED VIEW teams_without_admins AS
SELECT t.id AS team_id, t.name
FROM teams t
LEFT JOIN team_members m ON m.team_id = t.id AND m.role = 'admin'
GROUP BY t.id, t.name
HAVING COUNT(m.user_id) = 0;
```

For concurrent write skew — two admins both check 'are there 2+ admins?' and both downgrade simultaneously — the trigger alone is insufficient. Both sessions pass the count check before either commits:

```
-- Option 1: SERIALIZABLE isolation (SSI detects the read-write conflict)
BEGIN TRANSACTION ISOLATION LEVEL SERIALIZABLE;
SELECT COUNT(*) FROM team_members
WHERE team_id = 1 AND role = 'admin';
-- If count >= 2, proceed:
UPDATE team_members SET role = 'member'
WHERE user_id = 10 AND team_id = 1;
COMMIT;
-- PostgreSQL SSI aborts the second concurrent transaction.

-- Option 2: SELECT FOR UPDATE (locks existing admin rows)
BEGIN;
SELECT * FROM team_members
WHERE team_id = 1 AND role = 'admin'
FOR UPDATE;
-- Count the locked rows; if > 1, proceed.
UPDATE team_members SET role = 'member'
WHERE user_id = 10 AND team_id = 1;
COMMIT;
```

Key insight: the trigger enforces the invariant for single-session sequential writes. For concurrent sessions under snapshot isolation, both transactions can pass the count check before either commits — 'the anomalous behavior was possible only because the transactions ran concurrently.' SERIALIZABLE isolation or SELECT FOR UPDATE is required to prevent it. The materialized view is a read-only audit snapshot; it must be refreshed explicitly and cannot be queried transactionally inside the modifying transaction.

Stored procedure with explicit locking, validation, and error handling.

```
CREATE OR REPLACE FUNCTION redeem_points(
  p_user_id INT,
  p_points  INT
) RETURNS VOID LANGUAGE plpgsql AS $$
DECLARE
  current_points INT;
BEGIN
  IF p_points <= 0 THEN
    RAISE EXCEPTION 'Redemption amount must be positive, got %', p_points;
  END IF;

  -- Lock the account row to prevent concurrent redemptions from
  -- both reading the same balance and both passing the check
  SELECT points INTO current_points
  FROM loyalty_accounts
  WHERE user_id = p_user_id
  FOR UPDATE;

  IF current_points IS NULL THEN
    RAISE EXCEPTION 'Loyalty account % not found', p_user_id;
  END IF;

  IF current_points < p_points THEN
    RAISE EXCEPTION
      'Insufficient points for user %: balance % < requested %',
      p_user_id, current_points, p_points;
  END IF;

  UPDATE loyalty_accounts
  SET points = points - p_points
  WHERE user_id = p_user_id;

  INSERT INTO redemptions (user_id, points_used)
  VALUES (p_user_id, p_points);
END;
$$;

-- Usage
SELECT redeem_points(1, 100);
SELECT * FROM loyalty_accounts WHERE user_id = 1;  -- 400
SELECT * FROM redemptions WHERE user_id = 1;        -- 1 row

-- Test insufficient balance
SELECT redeem_points(2, 500);
-- ERROR: Insufficient points for user 2: balance 80 < requested 500
```

Why stored procedures are required for serial execution (VoltDB/Redis model):

In interactive client/server style, 'a lot of time is spent in network communication between the application and the database. If you were to disallow concurrency in the database and process only one transaction at a time, the throughput would be dreadful because the database would spend most of its time waiting for the application to issue the next query for the current transaction.'

A redemption takes three network round trips in interactive mode:
1. SELECT for balance check
2. UPDATE to deduct
3. INSERT for redemption record

With serial execution, each round trip is idle time — the single transaction thread sits blocked on network I/O. 'Systems with single-threaded serial transaction processing don't allow interactive multistatement transactions. Instead, the application must either limit itself to transactions containing a single statement or submit the entire transaction code to the database ahead of time, as a stored procedure.'

By bundling all three steps into one stored procedure, the serial executor runs the entire redemption without ever waiting for a network response. VoltDB uses Java/Groovy; Redis uses Lua scripts (EVAL). PostgreSQL's stored procedures can serve the same role when designing for high-throughput serialized workloads.

Comment: The FOR UPDATE in the procedure prevents the lost update race: two concurrent redemption requests both reading the same balance, both passing the check, and together over-redeeming. Without it, a user with 100 points could trigger two 80-point redemptions simultaneously — both see 100, both check 100 >= 80, both proceed, and the CHECK constraint fires only after the balance hits -60.
